// Leadership module content data

export const LMODULES={
  0:[{title:"Vision, Purpose & the Why",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to your first leadership module. Before we start, here is exactly what you will learn and what you will be required to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 What vision and purpose mean in a contact centre, and why they matter more than targets\n\u2022 How to write a one-sentence team mission that your agents can actually feel\n\u2022 What a BHAG is (Big Hairy Audacious Goal) and how to set one for your team\n\u2022 The 3 Elements of Vision and how to apply them to your floor\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Write your team mission statement (one sentence)\n\u2022 Set a 12-month BHAG for your team\n\u2022 Run a 15-minute team conversation sharing your mission and asking for input\n\u2022 Ask each agent in your 1:1s what they believe the purpose of their work is\n\u2022 Open one sales huddle with your mission instead of the targets\n\u2022 Document what happened and what you learned\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus activities woven into your existing team meetings, 1:1s, and huddles over two weeks. No extra meetings required.",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is Vision and Why Does It Matter?",content:"Let us start with something simple. Imagine two teams doing the exact same job.\n\nTeam A starts their Monday huddle like this: \'Okay team, target is 120 dials today. Let us get through it.\'\n\nTeam B starts their Monday huddle like this: \'Every call you make today could reconnect someone to holidays they have been missing. Their family dinners at hotels they love. Their status that makes them feel valued when they travel. Let us make 120 of those conversations happen.\'\n\nSame target. Same product. Completely different energy.\n\nThat difference is vision. Vision is the answer to the question: why does this team exist beyond hitting a number?\n\nThis matters more in outbound sales than almost anywhere else. Your agents are calling people who did not ask to be called. The only thing that makes that psychologically sustainable is belief. Belief in the product. Belief in the outcome for the member. And belief in the team they belong to.\n\nAn ALL Accor+ Explorer membership genuinely unlocks hotel rates, dining benefits, and recognition across hundreds of properties. When an agent calls a lapsed member, they are not chasing a target. They are potentially reconnecting someone to experiences that matter.\n\nYour job as a leader is to make that real. Not as a script line. As a shared belief your team actually holds.",img:"\u{1F4A1}"},
    {type:"video",title:"Start With Why",duration:"18:00",desc:"Simon Sinek explains the Why, How, What model. As you watch, focus on two things:\n\n1. How the Why model applies to your agents picking up the phone each morning. Why are they calling? Not what they are selling, but why it matters.\n\n2. How NASA\'s moon-landing goal aligned thousands of people around one clear objective. Your team is smaller, but the principle is the same. When people know why they are doing something, they bring more energy to the how.\n\nAfter watching, think about this: if someone asked one of your agents \'why do you work here?\' what would they say? And what do you want them to say?"},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: The 3 Elements of Vision",content:"Before we go further, read this article from LeaderGuide Australia. It explains the three elements that make a vision work, and why most teams skip the parts that matter most.\n\nRead it here: https://www.leaderguide.com.au/insights/the-3-elements-of-vision\n\nThe three elements are:\n\n1. Core Purpose: Why does your team exist beyond making money? This is not your KPI. This is the reason your team matters. For your team, it might be: \'We reconnect people to travel experiences that make their lives better.\'\n\n2. Core Values: How do you operate when no one is watching? These are the behaviours that define your team culture. Not the company values poster. The actual behaviours you see on the floor every day.\n\n3. BHAG (Big Hairy Audacious Goal): A stretch goal so clear and compelling that it aligns how people make decisions without you having to be in the room. We will cover this in detail in the next step.\n\nKey takeaway: visionary companies preserve a cherished core ideology while stimulating progress. A BHAG engages people. It reaches out and grabs them. It is tangible, energising, and highly focused. That is what you are building for your team.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is a BHAG?",content:"A BHAG stands for Big Hairy Audacious Goal. It is not your monthly target. It is not your quarterly KPI. It is the goal that makes your team say: \'That would be amazing if we pulled it off.\'\n\nHere is the difference:\n\nA target: \'Hit 18% conversion this month.\'\nA BHAG: \'Become the highest-converting outbound team in APAC by December, with zero voluntary resignations in our top 10 agents.\'\n\nA target tells you what to do. A BHAG tells you who to become.\n\nGood BHAGs for contact centre teams:\n\u2022 \'Achieve 95% agent retention for 12 consecutive months while maintaining top-quartile conversion.\'\n\u2022 \'Every new agent reaches full competency within 21 days, not 45.\'\n\u2022 \'Become the team that other Accor Plus markets fly in to learn from.\'\n\nBad BHAGs (these are just targets dressed up):\n\u2022 \'Hit 20% conversion\' (that is a target, not a BHAG)\n\u2022 \'Be the best team\' (too vague, not measurable)\n\u2022 \'Reduce attrition\' (no specificity, no emotion)\n\nA BHAG should make you slightly nervous and genuinely excited at the same time. If it does not feel a little scary, it is not big enough.",img:"\u{1F680}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Build Your Vision",prompt:"Now it is your turn. Write three things below. Be specific. Vague answers produce vague cultures.\n\n1. Your team mission (one sentence explaining why this team exists beyond hitting the sales target)\n\nGood example: \'We reconnect Accor members to experiences that matter, one conversation at a time.\'\nNot specific enough: \'We sell memberships and help customers.\'\n\n2. Your BHAG (the 12-month stretch goal that would galvanise your team)\n\nGood example: \'Become the highest-converting outbound team in APAC, achieving 22% conversion with zero churn in our top 10 agents by March 2027.\'\nNot specific enough: \'Improve our numbers.\'\n\n3. Your vivid description (paint the picture of what your team looks and feels like when the BHAG is achieved)\n\nGood example: \'Agents arrive early because they want to. New starters ask to join our team. The floor has energy. People celebrate each other\'s wins out loud. Our conversion rate is talked about in other markets.\'\nNot specific enough: \'The team is doing well.\'"},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: Team Meetings, 1:1s & Huddles",content:"Here is exactly what to do over the next two weeks. These activities use your existing meetings. No extra time required.\n\nWeek 1: Team Meeting (15 minutes)\n\u2022 Share your draft team mission with your team\n\u2022 Do NOT present it as final. Say: \'I have been thinking about why this team exists beyond hitting the number. Here is what I wrote. Does this feel true? What would you change?\'\n\u2022 Let the conversation run. Write down what they say\n\u2022 Share your BHAG. Ask: \'If we achieved this, what would that mean to you?\'\n\nWeek 1: 1:1 Conversations (add 5 minutes to each 1:1)\n\u2022 Ask each agent: \'What do you think is the purpose of what we do here, beyond hitting targets?\'\n\u2022 Do NOT correct their answer. Just listen and write it down\n\u2022 Notice the difference between agents who have a why and those who do not\n\nWeek 2: Sales Huddle (try this once)\n\u2022 Open your huddle with the mission statement instead of the targets\n\u2022 Say: \'Before I share today\'s numbers, I want to remind us why we are here: [your mission].\'\n\u2022 Then share the targets\n\u2022 Notice whether the energy in the room is different\n\nWeek 2: Follow-up 1:1s\n\u2022 For agents who had a clear sense of purpose: reinforce it. Tell them you noticed\n\u2022 For agents who struggled: share the team mission and ask what part of it resonates with them\n\u2022 Connect their personal motivation to the team mission",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The Disengaged Team",scenario:"It is Monday morning. Your team has been underperforming for three weeks. Dials are down, energy is flat, and two agents have started arriving late. You overhear one agent say to another: \'I just do not see the point of these calls.\' You have a team huddle in 10 minutes.\n\nYou have just written your team mission and your BHAG. What do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Address the lateness directly and reinforce KPI expectations",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"This addresses the symptom but not the cause. The agent said they do not see the point. Tightening targets without reconnecting them to purpose will create compliance, not commitment. Performance may lift briefly but the underlying disengagement remains. You have a mission statement now. This is exactly when to use it."},
      {label:"Open the huddle by sharing your team mission and asking the team what is making the work feel pointless right now",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is the strongest approach. You are leading with purpose rather than pressure. By sharing your mission and then asking what is making the work feel pointless, you create space for honest conversation. The mission gives them something to reconnect to. This is what vision-driven leadership looks like under real pressure. Notice that you are not ignoring the performance. You are addressing the root cause."},
      {label:"Cancel the huddle and have individual 1:1s instead to understand what is happening with each person",col:"#3b82f6",feedback:"1:1s are valuable but delaying the team conversation means the negative energy continues to spread. The comment was made publicly, which means others heard it. Addressing it in the team setting, with vulnerability and purpose, can shift the culture faster than individual conversations alone. Use the huddle to share the mission. Use the 1:1s later in the week to go deeper with each person."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these three questions honestly. There are no right answers. This is about what you are learning about yourself as a leader.\n\n1. What do your agents actually believe they are doing when they make calls? Not what you want them to believe. What do they actually believe right now? How do you know?\n\n2. When was the last time someone on your team felt genuinely proud of a call? What made that conversation different from the 119 others that day?\n\n3. What would have to be true about your leadership for every agent to feel their work here genuinely matters? Be honest about the gap between where you are and where that is."},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Share Your Vision",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts. Complete all three and document what happened.\n\nPart 1: Run the team conversation (Week 1)\nShare your mission and BHAG with your team in a meeting. Ask for their input. Do not present it as finished. Let them shape it. Document what they said and whether the mission evolved.\n\nPart 2: Ask the purpose question in 1:1s (Week 1-2)\nIn every 1:1 this fortnight, ask: \'What do you think is the purpose of what we do here, beyond hitting targets?\' Document each agent\'s answer. Notice who has a clear why and who does not.\n\nPart 3: Open a huddle with purpose (Week 2)\nOpen one sales huddle with your mission statement before the targets. Notice the energy difference. Document what you observed.\n\nThis is not a presentation exercise. This is a leadership experiment. You are testing whether purpose changes energy, and paying attention to what you learn about your team in the process."}
  ]}],
  1:[{title:"The Wellbeing Wheel",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to Module 2: The Wellbeing Wheel. This module is about understanding that you cannot lead a sustainable team from an unsustainable life.\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 What the Wellbeing Wheel is and why it matters for leaders in contact centres\n\u2022 The key principle: the owner of the wheel generates all the content, never the leader\n\u2022 How to facilitate a Wellbeing Wheel conversation without solving, suggesting, or judging\n\u2022 The connection between personal wellbeing and team performance\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Complete your own Wellbeing Wheel honestly (score each life domain 1 to 10)\n\u2022 Identify your lowest-scoring domain and commit to one action\n\u2022 Run the Wellbeing Wheel exercise with one agent in a 1:1\n\u2022 Document what you noticed about yourself and about them\n\u2022 Reflect on how wellbeing connects to performance on your floor\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus one facilitated 1:1 conversation (15 minutes) and your own wheel exercise (10 minutes).",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is Wellbeing and Why Does It Matter Here?",content:"Let us start with something real. Think about your best agent. The one who consistently hits target, stays positive on the phone, and lifts the energy of people around them.\n\nNow think about a time when that person had a bad week. Not a \u0027bad at work\u0027 week. A bad life week. Maybe a relationship issue. A health scare. A financial stress. What happened to their numbers?\n\nThey dropped. Because performance does not exist in a vacuum. Every agent who picks up the phone brings their whole life to that desk.\n\nMost contact centre leaders believe burnout is caused by long hours or difficult calls. It is not. Burnout is the gap between what someone\u0027s life demands and what they have the capacity to give.\n\nYou have agents calling lapsed members while their own life is lapsed. Relationships at 3 out of 10, health at 2 out of 10, financial wellbeing at 4 out of 10. That does not fix itself by hitting 120 dials. It fixes when someone sees the gap and starts closing it themselves.\n\nThe Wellbeing Wheel makes the gap visible. You facilitate the conversation. They own the action. That is the entire principle.",img:"\u{1F33F}"},
    {type:"video",title:"Working Towards Wellbeing",duration:"12:00",desc:"As you watch this video, focus on three things:\n\n1. The difference between what is important to you and what you think should be important to you. These are not the same thing. Notice how the wheel reveals this gap without judgment.\n\n2. How the wheel makes it instantly visible which areas of life need attention. It is not a test. It is data. Your data.\n\n3. The key principle that makes this work: the owner of the wheel must come up with all the content. The values, the scores, the solutions. Never someone else\u0027s goals for them. Your job as a leader is to hold the mirror, not to fix the reflection."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: The Wellbeing Wheel in Practice",content:"The Wellbeing Wheel conversation is fundamentally different from a performance review. You are not asking what the business needs from them. You are asking what they need from life, and what is currently missing.\n\nRead more about facilitation techniques here:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VJNMxYNzSUE\n\nThe wheel typically covers these life domains:\n\u2022 Physical Health: exercise, sleep, energy levels\n\u2022 Mental Health: stress levels, anxiety, emotional resilience\n\u2022 Relationships: partner, family, friendships, social connection\n\u2022 Financial Wellbeing: savings, debt, financial stress\n\u2022 Career and Growth: learning, development, sense of progress\n\u2022 Fun and Recreation: hobbies, downtime, things that recharge you\n\u2022 Physical Environment: living situation, workspace, comfort\n\u2022 Contribution: giving back, purpose beyond self\n\nEach domain is scored 1 to 10 by the person themselves. You do not score it for them. You do not suggest what the score should be. You ask the question and let them sit with the answer.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"How to Facilitate the Conversation",content:"Here is exactly how to run a Wellbeing Wheel conversation. Follow these steps precisely.\n\nBefore the conversation:\n\u2022 Complete your own wheel first. You cannot ask someone to be vulnerable if you have not done it yourself\n\u2022 Schedule 15 to 20 minutes in a private setting. Not at their desk. Not in a rush\n\u2022 Frame it clearly: \u0027This is not about work performance. This is about you as a whole person.\u0027\n\nDuring the conversation:\n\u2022 Draw the wheel with 8 segments (or use a template)\n\u2022 Ask them to label each segment with a life domain that matters to them\n\u2022 Ask them to score each domain from 1 to 10\n\u2022 Ask: \u0027Which domain stands out to you? Which gap feels the biggest?\u0027\n\u2022 Ask: \u0027What is one small thing you could do this week in that domain?\u0027\n\nCritical rules:\n\u2022 Do NOT suggest scores. Do NOT suggest actions. Do NOT say \u0027have you tried...\u0027\n\u2022 If they score something low, do not react with surprise or concern. Just ask: \u0027Tell me more about that.\u0027\n\u2022 Your only job is to ask questions and listen. They own everything else.",img:"\u{1F91D}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Complete Your Own Wheel",prompt:"Before you run this with anyone on your team, complete your own Wellbeing Wheel first. Be honest. No one sees this but you.\n\n1. Which life domain scored lowest on your own wheel? What number did you give it?\n\n2. What is one action you are committing to in that domain this week? Be specific. Not \u0027exercise more\u0027 but \u0027walk for 20 minutes before logging on, Monday Wednesday Friday.\u0027\n\n3. Which domain surprised you the most when you scored it? Was it higher or lower than you expected?"},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: 1:1s and Team Awareness",content:"Here is what to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWeek 1: Complete your own wheel and run one facilitated conversation\n\u2022 Complete your own Wellbeing Wheel (you have already started above)\n\u2022 Choose one agent for your first facilitated conversation. Pick someone you have a good relationship with\n\u2022 Run the 15-minute conversation following the steps from the facilitation guide\n\u2022 Document what happened (you will write this up in the mission)\n\nWeek 1: In your other 1:1s, add one question\n\u2022 Ask each agent: \u0027Outside of work, how are things going for you at the moment?\u0027\n\u2022 Do not push if they do not want to share. Just notice who opens up and who does not\n\u2022 This is not the full wheel exercise. It is building the muscle of asking about the whole person\n\nWeek 2: Reflect and expand\n\u2022 Review your own wheel action. Did you follow through?\n\u2022 Run the wheel with a second agent if you feel ready\n\u2022 In your team meeting, share (without naming anyone) that you have been exploring wellbeing conversations and what you have learned about the connection between life and performance\n\u2022 Notice whether any agents approach you afterwards wanting to talk",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The High Performer in Trouble",scenario:"Your top agent has hit target every month for 12 months. This week their conversion dropped to 8%. They look tired. In your 1:1, they say \u0027I am fine, just a rough week.\u0027 You suspect something deeper is going on.\n\nYou have just learned about the Wellbeing Wheel. What do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Take them at their word and check in again next week",col:"#f59e0b",feedback:"Respecting their answer seems kind, but \u0027I am fine\u0027 is rarely the full truth from someone whose performance has suddenly dropped. Waiting another week means another week of decline without support. Sometimes the most caring thing is to gently push past the surface. You could say: \u0027I hear you. And I also notice this is unusual for you. Would you be open to trying something with me?\u0027"},
      {label:"Introduce the Wellbeing Wheel and ask if they would be open to exploring it together",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is the strongest approach. The Wellbeing Wheel gives them a structured, non-judgmental way to see their own situation. You are not diagnosing them. You are holding up a mirror. Remember the key principle: they must generate all the content. Your job is to ask the questions and let them see the truth for themselves. Start with: \u0027I have been learning about something called the Wellbeing Wheel. It is not about work. It is about life. Would you be open to trying it?\u0027"},
      {label:"Share that you have noticed the performance change and ask directly what is going on at home",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"While direct, asking \u0027what is going on at home\u0027 can feel invasive and presumptuous. It assumes the issue is personal and puts them on the defensive. The Wellbeing Wheel approach lets them identify the domain themselves without you making assumptions about where the problem lies. Lead with the tool, not with your theory about their life."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these questions honestly after completing your facilitated wheel conversation.\n\n1. What did your own Wellbeing Wheel reveal that you have been avoiding looking at directly? Why have you been avoiding it?\n\n2. When you ran the wheel with an agent, what did you notice about them that you had not seen before? What was the gap between their work persona and their actual life?\n\n3. How would your leadership change if you treated wellbeing as a leading indicator of performance rather than a trailing excuse for poor results?"},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Run the Wheel",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts.\n\nPart 1: Complete your own wheel (Week 1)\nScore every domain honestly. Identify your lowest. Commit to one specific action. Follow through on it for two weeks.\n\nPart 2: Facilitate one wheel conversation (Week 1)\nRun the full Wellbeing Wheel exercise with one agent. Follow the facilitation guide exactly. Do not suggest. Do not solve. Hold the mirror.\n\nPart 3: Add the wellbeing question to all 1:1s (Week 1-2)\nIn every 1:1, ask: \u0027Outside of work, how are things going for you at the moment?\u0027 Notice who opens up and who deflects.\n\nDocument: Which domain scored lowest for you? Which domain scored lowest for the agent? What action did each of you commit to? What surprised you about the conversation?"}
  ]}],
  2:[{title:"Radical Candour",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to Module 3: Radical Candour. This module is about the difference between being kind and being nice, and why nice is often the most unkind thing a leader can be.\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 What Radical Candour is and how it differs from the four common feedback styles\n\u2022 Why most leaders default to Ruinous Empathy and what it costs their team\n\u2022 How to deliver direct feedback that is rooted in genuine care\n\u2022 The two-axis framework: Care Personally and Challenge Directly\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Identify where you currently default on the Radical Candour framework\n\u2022 Write a piece of Radically Candid feedback for one underperforming agent\n\u2022 Deliver that feedback in a real 1:1 conversation\n\u2022 Document what you said, how they responded, and what you agreed to do next\n\u2022 Reflect on what changed for you and for them\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus one feedback conversation in a scheduled 1:1.",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is Radical Candour and Why Does It Matter?",content:"Imagine this situation. You have an agent on your team who has been underperforming for six weeks. Their conversion rate is 9% against a team average of 19%. Their attitude is positive and they are well-liked by everyone.\n\nYou have mentioned their numbers casually twice. Once in a group setting (\u0027let us all push a bit harder\u0027) and once in a 1:1 (\u0027how are you finding the calls?\u0027). Neither conversation was direct. Neither named the gap. The agent left both conversations thinking everything was fine.\n\nSix weeks later, nothing has changed. Your manager asks why their numbers have not improved. You realise: they have never received clear feedback because you were protecting them from the truth.\n\nThis is Ruinous Empathy. You care about the person (that is genuine) but you are not willing to challenge them directly (that is the problem). The result: they are failing and they do not even know it.\n\nRadical Candour is the opposite. It means caring enough about someone to tell them the truth, while also caring enough to help them do something about it. It is not about being harsh. It is about being honest.\n\nThe difference between kind and nice matters enormously:\n\u2022 Nice avoids the truth to protect comfort\n\u2022 Kind delivers the truth to enable growth\n\nMost leaders default to nice. The best leaders choose kind.",img:"\u{1F4AC}"},
    {type:"video",title:"Radical Candour: How to Be a Better Boss",duration:"15:00",desc:"Kim Scott explains the Radical Candour framework. As you watch, focus on:\n\n1. The two-axis framework: Care Personally (vertical axis) and Challenge Directly (horizontal axis). These create four quadrants: Radical Candour (high care, high challenge), Ruinous Empathy (high care, low challenge), Obnoxious Aggression (low care, high challenge), and Manipulative Insincerity (low care, low challenge).\n\n2. Why Ruinous Empathy is the most common leadership failure. It feels like compassion but it is actually selfish because you are prioritising your own comfort over their growth.\n\n3. The practical advice: feedback should be immediate, specific, and delivered privately for criticism and publicly for praise. Do not save it for the performance review. Say it now."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: The Four Quadrants in Your Contact Centre",content:"Let us make this real for your floor. Here is what each quadrant looks like in a contact centre:\n\nRead more from Harvard Business Review on feedback:\nhttps://hbr.org/2019/03/the-feedback-fallacy\n\nRadical Candour (Care + Challenge):\n\u0027Your conversion rate is 9%. The team average is 19%. That gap is not closing on its own and I want to help you fix it. Let us look at your calls together this week and find what is happening.\u0027\n\nRuinous Empathy (Care without Challenge):\n\u0027You are doing great, keep it up!\u0027 (while knowing their numbers are the lowest on the team)\n\nObnoxious Aggression (Challenge without Care):\n\u0027Your numbers are terrible. Everyone else can do this. What is wrong with you?\u0027\n\nManipulative Insincerity (Neither Care nor Challenge):\nSaying nothing directly but complaining about them to other leaders behind their back.\n\nThe highest-performing teams are not the ones that receive the most criticism. They are the ones where people know exactly where they stand and what excellence looks like in their role.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"How to Deliver Radically Candid Feedback",content:"Here is a step-by-step guide for delivering feedback that is both direct and caring.\n\nBefore the conversation:\n\u2022 Write the feedback down first. First draft is the real draft. Do not soften it\n\u2022 Check: am I being specific? (not \u0027you need to improve\u0027 but \u0027your conversion rate is 9%, team average is 19%\u0027)\n\u2022 Check: am I leading with care? (not \u0027you are failing\u0027 but \u0027I want to help you succeed and right now there is a gap\u0027)\n\nDuring the conversation:\n\u2022 State the gap clearly. Use numbers. Do not hedge\n\u2022 Express genuine care: \u0027I am raising this because I care about your success here\u0027\n\u2022 Ask for their perspective: \u0027What do you think is happening?\u0027\n\u2022 Build a plan together: \u0027What can we do this week to start closing the gap?\u0027\n\u2022 Give them space to respond. Silence is okay. Let them process\n\nAfter the conversation:\n\u2022 Follow up within 48 hours. Ask how they are feeling about what you discussed\n\u2022 If they improve, recognise it immediately and specifically\n\u2022 If they do not, have the conversation again. Do not wait another six weeks",img:"\u{1F3AF}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Write Your Feedback",prompt:"Think of one agent on your team whose performance is currently below standard. Write the feedback you would give if you were being Radically Candid.\n\n1. Who is this feedback for? (name or initials)\n\n2. What is the specific gap? Use numbers. (e.g. \u0027Your conversion rate is X%. Team average is Y%. This has been the case for Z weeks.\u0027)\n\n3. Write the actual words you will say. Include both the care and the challenge. Do not dilute it. First draft is the real draft."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: Feedback in 1:1s and Team Culture",content:"Here is what to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWeek 1: Deliver one piece of Radically Candid feedback\n\u2022 Use the feedback you wrote in the previous step\n\u2022 Deliver it in your next scheduled 1:1 with that agent\n\u2022 Follow the step-by-step guide. State the gap. Express care. Ask their perspective. Build a plan\n\u2022 Document what happened (for the mission step)\n\nWeek 1: Self-audit your feedback patterns\n\u2022 After each 1:1 this week, ask yourself: was I Radically Candid, Ruinously Empathetic, or something else?\n\u2022 Notice which agents you find easiest to be direct with and which you avoid challenging\n\nWeek 2: Follow up and expand\n\u2022 Follow up with the agent you gave feedback to. Ask how they are going with the plan\n\u2022 If improvement is happening, name it specifically and publicly\n\u2022 Deliver one more piece of candid feedback to a different agent\n\u2022 In your team meeting, share (without naming anyone): \u0027I am working on being more direct with my feedback because I believe you all deserve to know exactly where you stand.\u0027",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The Feedback You Have Been Avoiding",scenario:"An agent on your team has been underperforming for six weeks. Their conversion rate is 9% against a team average of 19%. You have mentioned it casually twice but never had a direct conversation. Their attitude is positive and they are well-liked by the team.\n\nYour manager just asked you why their numbers have not improved. You know the answer: they have never received clear feedback because you have been protecting them from the truth.\n\nYou have a 1:1 with this agent tomorrow. What do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Schedule a formal performance improvement conversation with HR documentation",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"Jumping to formal process after six weeks of avoiding the conversation is unfair to the agent. They have never received clear, direct feedback about the gap. Starting with documentation before candour is Manipulative Insincerity. They deserve to hear the truth from you first, in a caring and direct conversation."},
      {label:"Have a direct 1:1 where you state the gap clearly, express that you care about their success, and build a plan together",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is Radical Candour. You care personally (you want them to succeed) and you challenge directly (the numbers are not acceptable). The key is saying it clearly: \u0027Your conversion is 9%. Team average is 19%. This gap has been here for six weeks and I should have raised it sooner. I want to help you close it. What do you think is happening?\u0027 First draft is the real draft. Do not dilute it."},
      {label:"Pair them with your top performer for shadowing and hope the numbers improve naturally",col:"#f59e0b",feedback:"This is Ruinous Empathy. You care about them but you are avoiding the direct conversation. Shadowing might help tactically, but the agent still does not know you see a problem. They deserve to know where they stand. Avoidance is not kindness. It is theft of their opportunity to improve."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these after you have delivered your feedback.\n\n1. Where are you currently operating in Ruinous Empathy? Which agents are you caring about but not challenging? What is the cost to them of your silence?\n\n2. When you delivered the candid feedback, what was harder: finding the words or actually saying them? What does that tell you about what has been holding you back?\n\n3. What would change on your floor if every agent knew exactly where they stand, every week, with both honesty and support?"},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Deliver Candid Feedback",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts.\n\nPart 1: Deliver one Radically Candid feedback conversation (Week 1)\nUse the feedback you wrote. State the gap with numbers. Express genuine care. Ask for their perspective. Build a plan together. Document what you said and how they responded.\n\nPart 2: Self-audit your feedback style (Week 1-2)\nAfter every 1:1 for two weeks, write down which quadrant you operated in: Radical Candour, Ruinous Empathy, Obnoxious Aggression, or Manipulative Insincerity. Notice your patterns.\n\nPart 3: Follow up and deliver a second feedback conversation (Week 2)\nFollow up with the first agent. Recognise improvement or address continued gaps. Then deliver candid feedback to one more agent.\n\nDocument: Who did you give feedback to? What did you actually say? How did they respond? What did you agree to do next? What quadrant did you find yourself defaulting to most often?"}
  ]}],
  3:[{title:"GROW Conversations",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to Module 4: GROW Conversations. This module teaches you the most important skill in leadership: how to help someone solve their own problems instead of solving them for them.\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 The GROW model: Goal, Reality, Options, Will\n\u2022 Why the sequence matters and what happens when you skip steps\n\u2022 The difference between coaching and telling, and why telling creates dependency\n\u2022 How to resist the urge to give answers and instead ask better questions\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Run one complete GROW conversation with an underperforming agent\n\u2022 Document each stage: the Goal they set, the Reality they described, the Options they generated, the Will they committed to\n\u2022 Practice the discipline of not telling during your 1:1s\n\u2022 Reflect on when you default to solving and what triggers that behaviour\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus one structured GROW conversation (20 minutes) and adjusted 1:1 approach across the fortnight.",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is Coaching and Why Does It Matter?",content:"Here is something uncomfortable. Most managers solve problems faster than their people do. And that is exactly why their people never learn to solve problems themselves.\n\nThink about your last five 1:1s. In how many of them did an agent bring you a problem and you told them what to do? \u0027Try this. Do that. Here is how I would handle it.\u0027\n\nIt feels efficient. It feels helpful. But every time you solve their problem, you teach them one thing: come to you next time.\n\nCoaching is the opposite. Instead of giving answers, you ask questions that help the other person think. It takes longer in the short term but it builds capability that compounds.\n\nAn agent who learns to diagnose their own conversion problem will fix the next problem themselves. An agent who is told the answer will wait for the next answer.\n\nThe GROW model gives you a structure for coaching conversations. It stands for:\n\nG: Goal. What do you want to achieve?\nR: Reality. What is happening right now?\nO: Options. What could you do?\nW: Will. What will you do?\n\nThe sequence matters. Starting with Reality before Goal leads to problem-focused thinking. Starting with Goal creates aspiration-focused thinking.",img:"\u{1F4A1}"},
    {type:"video",title:"The GROW Model: Coaching for Performance",duration:"12:00",desc:"As you watch this video, focus on three things:\n\n1. Why the sequence matters: Goal, Reality, Options, Will. Not the other way around. Starting with the Goal creates a positive frame. Starting with the Reality creates a deficit frame.\n\n2. The power of the question \u0027What have you tried?\u0027 This shifts ownership back to the person being coached. It says: I believe you have already been thinking about this. Show me.\n\n3. The difference between solving someone\u0027s problem for them and helping them solve it themselves. Watch for the moment where the coach resists the urge to tell and instead asks another question."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: The GROW Model in Practice",content:"Read more about the GROW model here:\nhttps://performancecoaching.co.nz/grow-model/\n\nThe GROW model is not a script. It is a discipline. Here is what each stage looks like in a contact centre context:\n\nGoal: \u0027What would you like to achieve with your conversion rate this month?\u0027\nNot: \u0027Your target is 18%.\u0027 Let them set their own goal. They often aim higher than you would set for them.\n\nReality: \u0027Where are you right now? What do you think is causing the gap?\u0027\nNot: \u0027Your numbers are low because you are not asking for the close.\u0027 Let them diagnose it. They are closer to the problem than you are.\n\nOptions: \u0027What could you do differently? What options do you see?\u0027\nNot: \u0027You should listen to James\u0027s calls and copy his approach.\u0027 Let them generate ideas. They are more likely to follow through on their own ideas than yours.\n\nWill: \u0027Which of those options will you commit to this week? What specifically will you do?\u0027\nNot: \u0027I want you to do X.\u0027 Commitment they generate is stronger than instruction you impose.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"The Questions That Make GROW Work",content:"Here are the exact questions to use in each stage. Keep this list open during your first GROW conversation.\n\nGoal questions:\n\u2022 \u0027What do you want to achieve?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027If this conversation goes well, what will be different afterwards?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027What does success look like for you in this area?\u0027\n\nReality questions:\n\u2022 \u0027Where are you right now in relation to that goal?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027What have you already tried?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027What do you think is getting in the way?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027On a scale of 1 to 10, where would you put yourself?\u0027\n\nOptions questions:\n\u2022 \u0027What could you do?\u0027 (then wait)\n\u2022 \u0027What else?\u0027 (always ask this, there is always another option)\n\u2022 \u0027If you had no constraints, what would you try?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027What would someone you admire do in this situation?\u0027\n\nWill questions:\n\u2022 \u0027Which option feels strongest to you?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027What specifically will you do this week?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027When will you do it?\u0027\n\u2022 \u0027How will I know you have done it?\u0027\n\nThe discipline is in the pause. When they ask you what to do, your response is: \u0027What do you think your options are?\u0027",img:"\u{1F3AF}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Plan Your GROW Conversation",prompt:"Choose one agent whose performance is below your team standard. Plan your GROW conversation here.\n\n1. Who will you coach? What is the specific performance gap? (Use numbers: their conversion, the team average, how long the gap has been there)\n\n2. What Goal question will you open with? Write it in your own words so it feels natural when you say it.\n\n3. What is your plan if they say \u0027I do not know, just tell me what to do\u0027? Write the reframe you will use to keep ownership with them."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: Coaching in 1:1s and Team Settings",content:"Here is what to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWeek 1: Run one complete GROW conversation\n\u2022 Use the plan you wrote in the previous step\n\u2022 Follow the GROW sequence. Do not skip stages\n\u2022 Keep the question list open as a reference\n\u2022 When you feel the urge to tell, pause and ask instead\n\u2022 Document the four stages (for your mission)\n\nWeek 1: Change your 1:1 default\n\u2022 In every 1:1 this week, when an agent brings you a problem, respond with: \u0027What do you think you should do?\u0027 before offering your view\n\u2022 Notice how many agents can self-solve when given the space\n\nWeek 2: Expand and follow up\n\u2022 Follow up on the GROW conversation from Week 1. Ask: \u0027How did it go with the action you committed to?\u0027\n\u2022 Run a second GROW conversation with a different agent\n\u2022 In your team huddle, try asking the team a coaching question instead of giving an instruction. For example: \u0027We are behind target today. What do you think we could do differently in the next two hours?\u0027\n\u2022 Notice the difference in energy when you ask vs when you tell",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The Agent Who Wants Answers",scenario:"You are running a GROW conversation with an agent whose conversion has dropped from 20% to 12% over the past month. You have asked \u0027What options do you have?\u0027\n\nThey look frustrated and say: \u0027I do not know. Just tell me what to do. You are the manager.\u0027\n\nWhat do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Give them two specific actions to try this week and check back on Friday",col:"#f59e0b",feedback:"This solves the immediate problem but creates dependency. Every time they hit a wall, they will come to you for the answer. Coaching takes longer in the short term but builds capability that compounds. If they never learn to generate their own options, they will never grow beyond needing you."},
      {label:"Acknowledge the frustration, then reframe: \u0027I hear you. And if you did know, what would you try first?\u0027",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is the coaching discipline. The reframe \u0027If you did know\u0027 is powerful because it bypasses the mental block. Most people do know what to try. They just want permission or validation. Your job is to create the space for them to think, not to think for them. Stay in the pause. They will answer."},
      {label:"Move to the Will stage and ask what they are committed to doing regardless",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"Skipping Options goes against the GROW sequence. Without exploring what they could do, any commitment will be shallow. The sequence matters: Goal creates aspiration, Reality creates honesty, Options create ownership, Will creates accountability. Jumping ahead produces a plan without buy-in."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these after your first GROW conversation.\n\n1. How often do you default to telling instead of coaching? What triggers that behaviour? Is it time pressure, impatience, or a belief that you know the answer better?\n\n2. In your GROW conversation, what moment surprised you? Did the agent generate an option you had not considered? What does that tell you about their capability?\n\n3. Think about the last time an agent surprised you with their own solution. What did you do differently in that conversation that created the space for them to think?"},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Run a Full GROW",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts.\n\nPart 1: Run a complete GROW conversation (Week 1)\nPick one agent whose performance is below standard. Run the full GROW structure. Document each stage: What Goal did they set? What Reality did they describe? What Options did they generate (not your suggestions)? What Will they commit to this week?\n\nPart 2: Change your 1:1 default (Week 1-2)\nIn every 1:1, when an agent brings a problem, respond with a question before offering a solution. Track how many times you successfully coached vs told.\n\nPart 3: Follow up and run a second GROW (Week 2)\nCheck in on the first agent\u0027s commitment. Run a second GROW with a different agent.\n\nDocument: What worked? Where did you struggle to stay in coaching mode? What changed in the agent\u0027s behaviour after the conversation?"}
  ]}],
  4:[{title:"Values-Based Leadership",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to Module 5: Values-Based Leadership. This module asks one simple question: what do you stand for when the targets are behind and the pressure is on?\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 What values-based leadership means in an outbound sales environment\n\u2022 What ethical fading is and how it happens gradually on your floor\n\u2022 How to define your leadership non-negotiables\n\u2022 How to facilitate a team values conversation\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Facilitate a 20-minute team values conversation\n\u2022 Ask your team: what three things will we never do to hit a target?\n\u2022 Write your own three leadership non-negotiables\n\u2022 Identify one recent moment where target pressure may have pushed toward a values compromise\n\u2022 Document what happened and what you learned\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus one team conversation (20 minutes) and personal reflection.",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What is Values-Based Leadership and Why Does It Matter?",content:"Let us start with a real situation that happens in outbound sales environments.\n\nIt is the last week of the month. Your team is 15% behind target. There is pressure from above. An agent suggests a tactic: call recently cancelled members and imply their cancellation \u0027did not process correctly\u0027 to get them back on a call.\n\nOther agents are listening. Some look uncomfortable. Some look interested. Everyone is watching you to see what you do.\n\nThis is the moment that defines values-based leadership. Not the team meeting where you present the company values poster. This moment. When the pressure is real and the shortcut is available.\n\nEthical fading is what happens when a leader under pressure gradually allows small compromises. Rushing the presentation. Glossing over terms. Using emotional pressure to close. Each one feels small. Together they erode the member experience and create chargebacks, complaints, and attrition.\n\nA values-based leader defines what the team will never do to hit a number. Not just what it will do. The line exists before the pressure arrives. When the pressure comes, the line holds because it was defined in advance.",img:"\u{1F6E1}\uFE0F"},
    {type:"video",title:"Leaders Eat Last",duration:"14:00",desc:"Simon Sinek explains the circle of safety and what leaders owe the people in their charge. As you watch, focus on:\n\n1. Sinek\u0027s argument about the circle of safety. As a leader, you create a space where your team feels safe enough to take risks, be honest, and do the right thing without fear. When that safety breaks, self-protection replaces collaboration.\n\n2. How a values-vacuum in leadership creates a self-protection culture on the floor. When agents do not know what the leader stands for, they default to whatever gets them through the day.\n\n3. What happens to team cohesion when short-term pressure overrides stated values. Trust is built slowly and broken quickly."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: Values and Goal Alignment",content:"Read this article on how clear goals and values align team behaviour:\nhttps://lattice.com/library/bhag-big-hairy-audacious-goals-guide\n\nThe key insight: a BHAG is not a budget goal. It is a rallying cry. A goal so clear and emotionally compelling that it aligns how people make decisions when no one is watching.\n\nCompanies that articulate this clearly outperform those that do not. Not because the goal is magical, but because clarity creates momentum.\n\nFor your team, the question is: what are the three values you would never compromise, even when the target is behind? If you cannot answer that instantly, neither can your agents. And when the pressure comes, they will make their own decisions about where the line is.\n\nExamples of team non-negotiables in outbound sales:\n\u2022 We never misrepresent the product to close a sale\n\u2022 We never pressure someone who has clearly said no\n\u2022 We always explain the cooling-off period and cancellation process\n\u2022 We treat every member the way we would want to be treated if they called us\n\nThese are not soft statements. They are hard lines that protect the member, the agent, and the business.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"How to Run a Team Values Conversation",content:"Here is how to facilitate a values conversation with your team. This works in a team meeting, a huddle, or a dedicated 20-minute session.\n\nStep 1: Set the frame (2 minutes)\nSay: \u0027I want to talk about something that is not about targets today. I want to talk about how we operate. Not what we do, but how we do it. Especially when things get hard.\u0027\n\nStep 2: Ask the question (10 minutes)\n\u0027What are three things this team should never do to hit a target?\u0027\nLet them answer. Write their answers on a whiteboard or shared screen. Do not judge or filter. Let everything come out.\n\nStep 3: Discuss and refine (5 minutes)\nGroup similar themes. Ask: \u0027Which of these feel most important to you? Why?\u0027\nLet the team prioritise. Their top three become your team non-negotiables.\n\nStep 4: Make it real (3 minutes)\nSay: \u0027These are our non-negotiables. I am committed to holding these, even when we are behind target. And I am asking you to hold me accountable too. If you ever see me or anyone on this team crossing these lines, speak up.\u0027\n\nThe power is in making it public, mutual, and permanent.",img:"\u{1F3AF}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Define Your Non-Negotiables",prompt:"Write your answers honestly. These become your leadership foundation.\n\n1. What three values did your team name most often when you asked \u0027what should we never do to hit a target?\u0027 What surprised you? What confirmed what you already knew?\n\n2. What are your three personal leadership non-negotiables? Be specific. Not \u0027respect\u0027 but what respect looks like on your floor when a call goes badly and the target is at risk.\n\n3. Describe one recent moment where target pressure may have pushed you or your team toward a values compromise. What happened? What would you do differently now?"},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: Living Your Values Under Pressure",content:"Here is what to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWeek 1: Facilitate the team values conversation\n\u2022 Run the conversation using the guide from the previous step\n\u2022 Document the three non-negotiables your team agrees on\n\u2022 Write them somewhere visible: a whiteboard, a Slack channel, or your team\u0027s shared space\n\nWeek 1: Write your own non-negotiables\n\u2022 Write your three personal leadership non-negotiables\n\u2022 Share them with your team: \u0027Here is what I stand for. Hold me to it.\u0027\n\nWeek 2: Test them under pressure\n\u2022 Notice moments where target pressure creates tension with your values\n\u2022 When it happens, refer back to the non-negotiables publicly\n\u2022 In your 1:1s, ask agents: \u0027Have you felt any pressure this week to do something that does not feel right?\u0027\n\u2022 If they say yes, thank them for being honest and address it",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The Target vs The Values",scenario:"Your team is 15% behind target with three days left in the month. A senior agent suggests a tactic: calling recently cancelled members and implying their cancellation \u0027did not process correctly\u0027 to get them back on a call. Other agents are listening.\n\nYou have just defined your team\u0027s non-negotiables. What do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Thank them for the initiative but explain clearly that this approach compromises member trust and is not how this team operates",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is values-based leadership under pressure. You are reinforcing what the team will never do, even when the target is at risk. Saying it publicly, when others are listening, sets the cultural standard. The short-term miss is recoverable. The trust damage from deceptive tactics is not. Reference your non-negotiables: \u0027We agreed we would never misrepresent to close a sale. That commitment holds today.\u0027"},
      {label:"Ask the team to discuss it and reach consensus on whether to use the approach",col:"#f59e0b",feedback:"Putting deceptive tactics to a team vote implies they are a legitimate option. Some things are not up for debate. Your non-negotiables exist for exactly this moment. A leader defines the line. The team operates within it. Consensus-seeking on ethical boundaries signals that values are flexible under pressure."},
      {label:"Allow it for the remaining three days and address the broader issue next month",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"This is ethical fading in real time. Short-term conversions will come at the cost of chargebacks, complaints, and attrition. More importantly, the team now knows that values bend when pressure rises. Once that precedent is set, it is very difficult to rebuild. The target will reset next month. Trust will not."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these after your team values conversation.\n\n1. What is one value you profess to your team but have not been fully living yourself this month? What would change if you started living it today?\n\n2. If your agents described your leadership style to someone who had never met you, what three words would they use? And what three words do you want them to use? What is the gap?\n\n3. Where does short-term target pressure most commonly create values tension in your team right now? What will you do about it this week?"},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Define and Live Your Values",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts.\n\nPart 1: Facilitate the team values conversation (Week 1)\nRun the 20-minute conversation with your team. Ask: \u0027What three things will we never do to hit a target?\u0027 Document their answers. Make the non-negotiables visible.\n\nPart 2: Share your personal non-negotiables (Week 1)\nWrite your three leadership non-negotiables and share them with your team. Say: \u0027Hold me to these.\u0027\n\nPart 3: Test under pressure (Week 2)\nNotice moments where target pressure creates values tension. Reference the non-negotiables when it happens. In your 1:1s, ask: \u0027Have you felt any pressure to do something that does not feel right?\u0027\n\nDocument: What three values did your team name? What are your personal non-negotiables? What happened when pressure tested them?"}
  ]}],
  5:[{title:"High Performance Standards",steps:[
    {type:"learn",title:"What You Will Learn & What You Will Do",content:"Welcome to Module 6: High Performance Standards. This is the final module. It brings everything together: vision gives direction, wellbeing gives capacity, candour gives honesty, coaching gives capability, values give integrity. Standards give clarity.\n\nWhat you will learn:\n\u2022 The difference between a standard, a target, and a stretch goal\n\u2022 Why most leaders accidentally lower standards without realising it\n\u2022 How to set one non-negotiable performance standard for your team\n\u2022 How to hold the standard through coaching, not pressure\n\nWhat you will be required to do:\n\u2022 Define one non-negotiable performance standard for your team (a specific metric)\n\u2022 Communicate it clearly to the team\n\u2022 Review at the end of the week: who met it and who did not\n\u2022 Address the gap through coaching (GROW), not by lowering the bar\n\u2022 Document what happened\n\nTime commitment: approximately 30 minutes of learning, plus one team communication and one week of tracking.",img:"\u{1F4CB}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"What Are Standards and Why Do They Slip?",content:"Here is something that happens on almost every contact centre floor. Gradually. Invisibly.\n\nThree months ago, your team conversion target was 18%. Your team averaged 20%. Life was good. Then a few agents left. New agents joined. One month the average dipped to 16%. You thought: \u0027They are still ramping up.\u0027 The next month it was 14%. You thought: \u0027It is a tough month.\u0027 This month it is 13%. Nobody has said anything.\n\nThe standard has slipped. Not because anyone decided to lower it. Because nobody decided to hold it.\n\nThis is how standards erode. Not through dramatic failure but through quiet drift. And the cost is enormous: your top performers notice that mediocrity is tolerated, your new agents learn that \u0027good enough\u0027 is good enough, and your bottom performers have no incentive to improve.\n\nThree levels of performance exist on every team:\n\n1. The Standard: the minimum acceptable level. This is the floor. Performance below this is not okay. It is not average. It is the line.\n\n2. The Target: where you expect consistent operation. Above the standard, within reach for everyone.\n\n3. The Stretch: what your top performers hit. This is what you coach toward and celebrate when achieved.\n\nMost leaders confuse the standard with the target. When the standard drops, the target drops with it. And the stretch disappears entirely.",img:"\u{1F4C8}"},
    {type:"video",title:"Setting and Holding Standards",duration:"10:00",desc:"As you watch, focus on two critical ideas:\n\n1. High standards without coaching creates pressure. If you set the bar high but do not help people reach it, you create anxiety and resentment. People will either burn out trying or give up.\n\n2. Coaching without standards creates drift. If you coach people but never define what excellent looks like, everyone has a different definition of good enough. There is no anchor.\n\nYou need both. Always. The standard says \u0027this is where the bar is.\u0027 The coaching says \u0027here is how I will help you get there.\u0027 Neither works without the other."},
    {type:"learn",title:"Read: Defining Your Standard",content:"A standard must be:\n\u2022 Specific: a number, not a feeling. \u0027Minimum 18% conversion\u0027 not \u0027do your best\u0027\n\u2022 Measurable: you can track it daily or weekly\n\u2022 Communicated: every agent knows what it is\n\u2022 Consistent: it does not change based on how the month is going\n\u2022 Supported: coaching is available for anyone below it\n\nExamples of good standards for contact centre teams:\n\u2022 Conversion rate: minimum 18% on outbound calls\n\u2022 Average handle time: 8 to 12 minutes per qualified conversation\n\u2022 Quality score: minimum 85% on call quality assessments\n\u2022 Dial volume: minimum 80 dials per shift\n\nExamples of bad standards:\n\u2022 \u0027Do your best\u0027 (not specific)\n\u2022 \u0027Be like James\u0027 (not measurable, creates comparison not clarity)\n\u2022 \u0027Hit target\u0027 (the target is not the standard, the standard is the floor)\n\nThe question is: what is the one metric where you will draw a clear line this week? Below this line, we coach. At this line, you are meeting standard. Above this line, you are performing.",img:"\u{1F4D6}"},
    {type:"learn",title:"How to Communicate and Hold a Standard",content:"Communicating a standard is not making an announcement. It is making a commitment. Here is exactly how to do it.\n\nStep 1: Define it clearly (before the team meeting)\n\u2022 Choose one metric. Not three. One. The most important one right now\n\u2022 Set the number. This is your standard (the floor), not your target (the expectation)\n\u2022 Know where each agent currently sits relative to it\n\nStep 2: Communicate it (in a team meeting)\n\u2022 Say: \u0027I want to be transparent about our performance standard. The minimum conversion rate for this team is [X]%. Here is where each of us stands.\u0027\n\u2022 Share each person\u0027s number (or share privately if that is more appropriate for your culture)\n\u2022 Say: \u0027If you are below this standard, I am here to help you get there. We will work on it together. But the standard itself does not move.\u0027\n\nStep 3: Hold it (every day, every week)\n\u2022 Track it visibly. Share progress daily or weekly\n\u2022 When someone falls below: coach (use GROW). Do not ignore it\n\u2022 When someone meets it: recognise it. \u0027You hit standard this week. Well done.\u0027\n\u2022 When someone exceeds it: celebrate it publicly. This is your stretch performer. They set the example",img:"\u{1F3AF}"},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Set Your Standard",prompt:"Define your standard right now.\n\n1. What is the one performance metric you are setting as your non-negotiable standard this week? What is the specific number? (e.g. \u0027Minimum 18% conversion rate on outbound calls\u0027)\n\n2. Who on your team is currently below this standard? List them and their current number.\n\n3. For the person furthest below the standard, what is your plan? Not \u0027lower the bar\u0027 but \u0027close the gap.\u0027 What coaching conversation will you have and when?"},
    {type:"learn",title:"Your Activities: Setting, Tracking, and Holding",content:"Here is what to do over the next two weeks.\n\nWeek 1: Set and communicate the standard\n\u2022 Define your one metric and number\n\u2022 Communicate it in your next team meeting using the script above\n\u2022 Share where each agent stands (publicly or privately)\n\u2022 For anyone below standard, schedule a coaching conversation using GROW\n\nWeek 1: Track daily\n\u2022 At the end of each day, check where each agent sits\n\u2022 In your daily huddle, share progress without judgment: \u0027Here is where we are today\u0027\n\u2022 Recognise anyone who has moved closer to standard\n\nWeek 2: Hold the line\n\u2022 Review the week. Who met standard? Who did not?\n\u2022 For those who met it: recognise them specifically\n\u2022 For those who did not: run a GROW conversation. What was their goal? What happened? What will they do differently?\n\u2022 Do NOT lower the standard. Do NOT say \u0027let us aim for 15% instead.\u0027 Hold the line and raise the capability\n\nWeek 2: Celebrate your stretch performers\n\u2022 Identify your top performer. What standard do they hold that others do not?\n\u2022 Ask them to share one thing they do differently in a team huddle. Peer learning is powerful",img:"\u{1F4DD}"},
    {type:"apply",title:"Scenario: The Standard Has Slipped",scenario:"Your team conversion target is 18%. Three months ago, your team averaged 20%. Over the past eight weeks, the average has drifted to 14%. No one has said anything. The lowest performer is at 8% and the highest is at 22%.\n\nYou have a team meeting tomorrow morning. What do you do?",choices:[
      {label:"Reset the standard publicly, show where each person stands, and offer coaching support for everyone below the line",col:"#10b981",feedback:"This is clarity with support. You are not lowering the bar. You are naming the gap and offering to help close it. Saying \u0027Here is our standard. Here is where each of us stands. I am here to help you get there.\u0027 removes ambiguity. The combination of clear standards plus coaching is what high-performance leadership looks like."},
      {label:"Focus on the top performer, celebrate their 22%, and hope it motivates the rest",col:"#f59e0b",feedback:"Celebrating one person without addressing the gap sends a mixed message. The underperformers hear \u0027great job to them\u0027 but not \u0027here is what I expect from you.\u0027 Recognition without accountability creates a two-tier culture where standards only apply to those who choose to meet them."},
      {label:"Lower the target to 15% temporarily to rebuild confidence, then raise it later",col:"#ef4444",feedback:"Lowering the standard teaches the team that underperformance is self-correcting. The bar drops, people meet the lower bar, and the original standard becomes aspirational rather than expected. You never raise it back. The drift becomes permanent. Hold the standard and raise the capability."}
    ]},
    {type:"reflect",title:"Deep Reflection",prompt:"Answer these at the end of your two weeks.\n\n1. Where have you been lowering standards to avoid difficult conversations? What has that cost your team in performance, culture, and credibility?\n\n2. Who is the highest performer on your team? What standard do they hold for themselves that the rest of your team does not? How can you make their standard visible to others?\n\n3. What would change on your floor if every agent knew exactly what the standard was, where they stood, and that you would coach them to get there but never lower the bar?"},
    {type:"mission",title:"Mission: Set and Hold a Standard",brief:"Your two-week mission has three parts.\n\nPart 1: Define and communicate one standard (Week 1)\nChoose one metric. Set the number. Communicate it to your team in a meeting. Be transparent about where each person stands.\n\nPart 2: Track and coach daily (Week 1-2)\nTrack the metric every day. Share progress in huddles. For anyone below standard, run a GROW coaching conversation. For anyone who meets or exceeds standard, recognise them.\n\nPart 3: Review and hold (Week 2)\nAt the end of the fortnight, review: Who met standard? Who did not? Did you hold the line or find yourself wanting to lower it? What coaching conversations made the biggest difference?\n\nDocument: What standard did you set? How did you communicate it? Who met it? Who did not? What did you do about the gap? Did you hold the line?"}
  ]}]

};
